div.head: Complaint of Forest Ashfield.
div.p:
[IMG_0375] [IMG_0376]
Mai ii 1709
[signature]
To the right honourable William Lord Cowper Baron of Wingham Lord high Chancillour of Great Britaine
Humbly complaining sheweth unto your Lordshipp your Orator Forrest Ashfeild of Tickenham in the County of Somersett gentleman son and heire of Eleanor Glanvile deceased late wife of Richard Glanvile sometime of the same place gentleman by Edmund Ashfield Esquire her former
Husband (which said Eleanor was the only Child and heire of William Goodrick Esquire and Eleanor his wife your Orators Grandfather and Grandmother and your Orators said Grandmother was the only Child of Rice Davis Esquire by Mary his third wife your Orators Great Grandfather and great
Grandmother by the Mothers side That the said Rice Davis in his life time being seized in fee simple or of some other good Estate of Inheritance to him and his heires of and in the Mannor of Tickenham and the third parte of the Mannor of Rodney Stoke and a Farme and Lands in the parish of
Backwell called Backwell parks with their appurtenances all in the said County of Somersett and of and in diverse other Lands Tenements rents and hereditaments there and else where in the same County of the yearely vallue of five hundred pounds and upwards did on or about the
Sixteenth day of December which was in the yeare of our Lord one Thousand Six hundred and twenty Four by Deed of that date for good and vallueable consideracions well and sufficiently settle and assure the same premisses or the greatest parte thereof on him and the said Mary his
wife and the Issue of their twoe bodyes or to some such like or other use or uses as by the same Deed had your orator the same to produce would appeare and that they had Issue only one daughter the said Eleanor your Orators Grandmother And that your orators said Great Grandmother
died And that your orators said Great GrandFather survived her and that afterwards in or aboute August in the Yeare one thousand Six hundred and thirty Eight upon a treaty of marriage between one Nicholas Poyntz Esquire and your orators said Grandmother your orators said
Greate Grand Father did contract and article to settle the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof after his owne death on the said Nicholas and Eleanor your orators Grandmother and the Issue of their twoe Bodyes with remainder to the Issue of her body or to some such like or other use or
uses as by the said Articles or Contract had your Orator the same to produce might appeare and that the same were or ought to have been pursueant thereto so settled and that the said marriage was had between the said Nicholas Poyntz and your orators said Grandmother and that
the said Rice Davis soone afterwards died After whose death the said Nicholas Poyntz and Eleanor his wife your orators said Grandmother did levy a fine and suffer a common recovery of the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof the uses whereof were declared to them the said Nicholas
and Eleanor and the Issue of their twoe Bodyes With remainder to the Issue of the Body of the said Eleanor or to some such like or other use or uses as by the Chirographs of the said Fine and Exemplificacion of the said recovery and the Deeds declareing the Uses thereof had your orator the same to
produce would more at large appeare And your Orator further sheweth that the said Nicholas Poyntz afterwards in or about the yeare one Thousand Six hundred and Fifty died without Issue And that soone afterwards to witt in or about the yeare one thousand Six hundred and Fifty one your
orators said Grandmother intermarried with the said William Goodrick your orators GrandFather And that thereupon the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof were either by your orators said Grandmother before the said marriage or by your orators said GrandFather and Grandmother
after the said marriage by certeyne assureances in the Lawe settled and assured to the use of your orators said GrandFather and Grandmother and the Issue of their twoe Bodyes with other remainders over or to some such like or other use or uses as by the Deeds thereof had your Orator the same to
produce would more at large appeare and your orator futher sheweth that your orators said GrandFather and Grandmother had Issue only the said Eleanor your orators said mother And that in or about the yeare one thousand Six hundred and Fifty Eight your orators said Grandmother
died and that soone afterwards your Orators said GrandFather alsoe died leaveing your orators said mother their only Child an Infant of very tender yeares And that all and every the Settlements and assureances aforesaid were such and made and expressed in such sorte as that by vertue thereof
or of some of them the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof are descended and come or ought to have descended or come to and to be and have been from his said mothers death had and enjoyed by your Orator and his heires either generall or speciall as thereby will appeare when the same shall be
produced and your Orator further sheweth to your Lordship that after the death of your Orators said GrandFather and Grandmother your Orators said mother before she atteyned the Age of One and Twenty yeares (vizt.) in or about the yeare of our Lord one thousand Six hundred Seventy and Five
intermaried with the said Edmond Ashfeild her first husband your orators said Father by whome she had Issue only two Children (vizt) your orator and his sister Mary Ashfeild and that after the Birth of your Orator in the life time of his said Father (vizt.) in or about the yeare of our Lord
one thousand Six hundred and seventy seven she your orators said Mother haveing before that time etteyned her full age of one and twenty yeares and takeing into Consideracion that altho your Orators Father was a gentleman of a worthy family as being nephew of Sr Thomas Ashfeild late of
Chesham in the County of Bucks Knight yett had but a small Fortune and that he upon his marrying with her and to oblidge her had quitted a gentile and profitable profession which he had been bred to and by which he might yearely have gotten as much as the Income of her Estate amounted to or more And
that he had behaved himselfe in all respects very oblidgeing to her And therefore being minded and intending to settle the greatest parte of her Estate on him and your Orator In order thereto in Michalmas Terme in the same yeare your orators said Father and mother did in due forme of Lawe acknowledge and
levy to Sidney Bere Esquire and Robert Forest Esquire an Uncle of your orators said Father one Fine [sure] Cognizance &c of (amongst other things) all the said premisses Excepting the said part of the said Manor of Rodney Stoke which Fine was pursued with proclamacions according to the Statute in that
behalfe and that the said Fine was duely declared by Deed in writeing under the hands and seales of your orators said Father and motherr or one of them to[eunre] to the uses of your said orators said Father and mother for their lives respectively and after their deceases to or to the use of or in trust for
your orator in Taile or for some other Estate [viz?] Estates well knowne to the Confederates herein after named and which they ought but refuse to discover and your Orator further sheweth that your orators said Father and mother did (as is pretended) make and execute some other Deed pretended to
beare date on or about the Eighteenth day of January in the same yeare declareing the said Fine to be and enure to such uses intents and purposes as your orators said mother by her last will and Testament in writeing or by any other writeing under her hand and seale attested by twoe or three credible
Wittnesses should lymitt direct and appoint But your Orator further sheweth that if any such Deed was really made and executed yett the same void in Lawe and of none Effect for that the Uses of the said Fine had been soe before declared as aforesaid And she your Orators said mother being
sensible thereof and that the said premisses really belonged to your Orator as aforesaid did afterwards by some writeing pursuent to such Deed lymitt direct and appoynt the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof to your Orator after the death of them your Orators said Father and mother
owne of them and your Orator further sheweth that all the said Deeds Settlements assureances and writeings before mencioned with many others touching the said premisses were by your orators said Frather and mother or one of them deposited and left in the hands of one Edward Gorges of Wraxall
in the said County of Somersett Esquire lately deceased to be by him kept in Trust for them your orators said Father and mother and to preserve your orators Interest therein and Evidence thereof and your orator further sheweth that soone afterwards your orators said Father died leaveing your
Orators said mother his [relict] and twoe small Children by her (vizt.) your orator and the said Mary his Sister and your Orator further sheweth that after the death of your Orators said Father (vizt.) in or about November one Thousand Six hundred and Eighty Five she your orators
said mother interrmarried againe with one Richard Glanville gentleman a person then of a small Fortune and that upon the occasion of that marriage she did by some other Deed or assurance in the Lawe further settle and assure the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof on
your Orator to putt it further out of her power (if it could be) upon any Importunity or prevailance of her said second husband to doe any act to barre or prejudice your Orators Title and Interest in or to the said premisses or any parte thereof and that such Deed was alsoe
deposited in the hands of the said Edward Gorges for your orators Benefitt and your orator further sheweth to your Lordshipp that your Orators said Mother cohabited very comfortably with the said Richard Glanvile for some yeares and had twoe other Children
by him (vizt.) Richard Glanvile and Eleanor Glanvile both still liveing But that at length the said Richard Glanville and your Orators said mother had greate Controversies and Differences which arise from his the said Richard Glanviles attempting and endeavouring to
obteyne her to make some settlement of the said premisses or parte thereof on him and which she avoided doeing by useing and giveing severall arguments and reasons for her not soe doeing and (amongst others that the premisses were settled on your Orator as aforesaid
and that therefore twas out of her power to settle the same or any parte thereof on him the said Richard Glanvile But he the said Richard Glanvile resolveing [to run] the adventures thereof and proposeing to himselfe that if he could but obteyne any settlement of the
[IMG_0377; IMG_0378]
premisses to be made on him by your Orators said Mother he would afterwards finde meanes to gett the former settlements into his hands and to destroy conceale or otherwise avoid the same continued his attempts on your Orators said mother to obteyne his said Ends
which occasioned severall suites and Controversies betweene them upon which they seperated and the said Richard Glanvile in greate displeasure went away from your Orators said mother and [abhabited] from her in parts remote from and unknowne to her till her
her death which happened aboute one yeare since in the life time of the said Richard Glanvile without haveing ever conversed with or seene one another from the time of their seperacion as aforesaid which was in the yeare one thousand six hundred and ninety three soe that your
Orators said Mother had noe power or oppertunity to make any alteracions of the said settlements or any of them or to dispose of the said premisses or any parte thereof or to disinheritt your Orator of the same soe as that the said premisses and every parte thereof upon the death
of your Orators said mother ought to have come or descended to your Orator by vertue of the severall Deeds Settlements assureances wayes or meanes aforesaid or otherwise as heire of the Bodyes as well of his said GrandFather and Grandmother as of his said mother or as
heire att Lawe to her But nowe so it is may it please your Lordshipp that Sir Henry Goodrick of Ribston in the County of York Baronet combineing and confederateing to and with Thomas Edwards of the City of Bristoll Esquire and William Sambre of Lyon's Inne in the parish of St.
Clements Dane in the County of Middlesex gentleman and Thomas Merricke nowe resideing in Lincolnes Inne in the County of Middlesex Esquire and alsoe with severall persons as yett unknowne to your Orator (who as they shall be discovered your Orator prays may be made
partyes to this Bill with apt matter and words to charge them) how totally to defeate and disinheritt your Orator of all the said premisses and they the said Confederates or some of them haveing unduely gotten into their or some of their Custody or power or into the Custody or
power of some other person or persons in trust for them or some of them all or most of them the Deeds settlements assureances and writeings aforesaid and of other the Deeds Evidences and writeings relateing to the title of the said premisses The greatest parte of which settlements
assurances Deeds and writeings your Orator expressly charges to have been gotten into the Custody of the said Mr. Edwards from the said Mr. Gorges in the life time of your Orators said Mother at or about the time of the said suites and controversies betweene your
Orators said Mother and her said husband Mr Glanvile upon pretence that the same were necessary to be produced in the said suites and Controversies on behalf of your Orator and his said mother to shewe that the said premisses were soe settled on your Orator as
aforesaid or otherwise and upon his the said Mr. Edwards's promise to returne the same againe as soon as those suites and Controversies were over whereupon a Box and large parcell of writeing and (amongst others) the severall Deeds Settlements assureances and writeings
aforesaid and other Deeds and Settlements whereby the said premisses were settled or appointed to or to the use of or in trust for [use?] your Orator [wers] by the said Mr Gorges delivered to the said Mr Edwards for the purpose aforesaid But he never returned the same to the said
Mr Gorges although the said Mr Gorges often demanded the same for which dealing of his the said Mr Edwards's he the said Mr Gorges often to his death complayned of and much blaymed him and other Deeds Evidences and writeings and amongst them some other
Settlements Deeds of appointments or other assureances of the said premisses or the greatest parte thereof made on or in favour of your orator were by the said Confederates upon the death of your Orators said Mother found in her Custody and taken into theirs and thereupon
they the said Confederates or some of them have not only violently intruded into the possession of great[est] parte of the premisses But have by force expelled your Orator out of other partes thereof and deteyne the same and the rents and profitts thereof from your
Orator and have brought an accion against your Orator which was affirmed to your Orator required twenty thousand pounds baile on purpose to force your Orator to release the said premisses to them or some of them or to comply with some other their Ends and
threaten to comence other accions and suites against your Orator and his tennants whoe is and are yett in possession of the rest of the said premisses and not only so But they the said Confederates have cutt downe greate quantityes of Timber on such partes of the
premisses as are by them possessed as aforesaid and threaten to cutt downe the rest of the Timber groweing there on and to comitt other waste and Destruccons on the said premisses and have received and taken the rents Issues and profitts thereof and have ever since
sett and disposed of the same att their pleasure and continue soe to doe pretending and giveing out in Speeches that your Orators said Father and mother in their lifetime did by Deed and Fine in the yeare of our Lord one thousand Six hundred and Seventy Eight
with other persons unknowne to your Orator mortgage the said premisses to one Sir Thomas Higgons Knight for the terme of one thousand yeares for secureing the payment to him of one thousand pounds and Interest and thatsuch Fine was declared to enure to
the use of the said Sir Thomas Higgons for the said terme to confirme the said mortgage and afterwards to such uses as your Orators said mother by Deed or will should appoint and for default of such appointment then to the use of your Orators said Mother her
heires and assignes and that the [said] Mortgages and terme were afterwards in or aboute the yeare of our Lord one thousand six hundred and Eighty after your Orators said Fathers death assigned to Dame Anne Gonning widdow by the said Sir Thomas
Higgons and charged by your Orators said mother with one hundred pounds principall money more and that the same was afterwards assigned to Sir William Merrick knight deceased late Father of the said Thomas Merrick or to some person or persons in
trust for him and that the same premisses were or have been charged by your Orators said mother to the said Sir William Merricke and Thomas Merricke or one of them as a Security for three thousand pounds or some other greate summe of money and that the
said Thomas Merricke is the sole Executor of the last will and Testament of the said Sir William Merricke and that the said three thousand pounds or other summe for which the said premisses are pretended soe to be mortgaged and severall yeares
Interest pretended alsoe to be due for the use or forbearance thereof was unpaid and unsatisfyed att the time of your orators said mothers death and therefore he the said Thomas Merricke pretends that he had and hath a right to enter upon and enjoy all or so much
of the premisses as stands mortgaged and engaged for security and payment of his said Debt and Interest and that the same are become forfeited and vested in him by the Breach of Condicion in the Deeds of mortgage to him thereof made and they the said Confederates
doe alsoe pretend that your orators said mother before her intermarrying with the said Mr Glanvile by some Conveyances and assurances in the Lawe bearing date in or about the Month of November which was in the yeare of our Lord one thousand six
hundred Eighty and Four did convey and assure all the said premisses (amongst other Lands at Loxton in the said County of Somersett which have been since sold) to the said Edward Gorges and one William Rogers Esquire and their heires to the use of them and their
heires forever and that the same was by some other Deed or writeing declared and agreed by and betweene your Orators said in other and the said Mr Gorges Mr Rogers and Mr Glanvile that the said Conveyance and assurance were soe made to the said Mr
Gorges and Mr Rogers and their heires upon trust that the said Mr Gorges and Mr Rogers and their heires should from time to time make such Leases Grants and Estates of the said Mannors Tenements and premisses or any parte or parcell thereof and alsoe
should permitt and suffer the rents Issues and profitts of the premisses to be had received taken and enjoyed by such person or persons as your Orators said Mother by any writeing or writeings Deed or Deeds under her hand and Seale testifyed by three or more
Wittnesses (which writeings Deeds or Will the said Mr Glanvile did as is pretended agree and consent that your Orators said mother might make and that he did thereby enable her to make the same as if she were a Feme Sole) should from
time to time lymitt order direct or appoynt and for want of such direction and appoyntment then as the heire of your Orators said Mother should direct and appoynt.
[f. 2 IMG_0383; IMG_0385; IMG_0387] [IMG_9306 for reference]
And they the said Confederates doe alsoe give out and pretend that your Orators said Mother did pursuant to her power aforesaid or some of them by certain Deeds in writing under her hand and Seale limitt direct or appoint the said premisses or the greatest part thereof [or Some Estates]
termes or Interests therein first by one or more Deed to your Orator afterwards by another Deed to her said husband Glanvile and after that by another Deed to one Thomas Co[u]les gentleman & Richard Melli[e]champ deceased But that Your Orators said Mother had Compelled & avoided the Same as they
appeared to them the said Confederates they pretend after Your Orators said Mothers death And they the said Confederates further give out & pretend That Your Orator was all his time very extravagant in his way of living & expences beyond his Quality & his Mothers for [time] to maintein him and that he was very
disobedient & undutifull to his said Mother in severall respects & perticularly [his] forming from the Errors of the Church of Rome In [which] he was bredd & conforming to the discipline & Doctrine of the Church of England And that it doth appeare by Severall [Lnep] under his hand whereby he hath
owned such his offence And that all her other Children were likewise disobedient to their said Mother & became protestants And that she Your Orators said Mother was not the reall Child of the said William Goodricke & Eleanor his Wife but a Changling & Imposter And that She your
Orator's said Mother was Conscious thereof & her wrongdoeing in withholding the premisses from the rightfull heires thereof And that for the reasons aforesaid She your Orators said Mother resolved to disinherit Your Orator & deprive all the rest of her Children of the [premisses] &
every part thereof & to bestowe the same to the Family of the Goodricks to whom (as the Confederates pretend) the same did belong And they the said Confederates doe pretend & give out that She your Orators said Mother did on about the thirtyeth day of July One thousand seven hundred
and Five make and ordain her last Will & Testament in writing & that she thereby willed & devised that the said Trustees Mr Gorges & Mr Rogers out of the rents & profitts or by leasing [made] Small rents or Mortgage or sale of the premisses or any part thereof Should in the first place Satisfye
& pay to the said Mr Merricke Two thousand & Five hundred pounds & Interest due by Mortgage of the greatest parte of the premisses & in the next place to your Orator & here other Sonn & eldest daughter ten pounds a peice & to your Younger daughter Five shillings a week for her life And that as concerning
the premisses after the debts maintenance & porcions aforesaid should be paid [shredecrised] the Same to the Said Sir Henry Goodrick then Henry Goodrick Esquire his heires & assgines for ever and that [s]he gave some Legacys to other persons particularly One hundred pounds a peice to two Romish priests [viz] She did order and
direct her said Trustees Gorges & Rogers to pay out of the rents & profitts of the pr[eunes] within One Yeare after her death & that she made the said Sir Henry Goodrick Executor of her said Will And they the said Confederates doe also give out & pretend that your Orator said Mother did by Some other deed limitt order declare & appoint
the said Trustees their heires & assignes imediatly after her decease to grant & convey all the p[remisses] & in such manner as Councell should advise unto the said Sir Henry Goodrick his heires & assignes forever he paying the mortgage money due the [teons] & all other her just debts & the Legacys in her [p]aid
[Wicell] that the Same was made with power of [ceeocacion] in the presences of three or more Substantiall witnesses whereof two or more to be acting Justices of the peace and the said Trustees both dying soon after the death of your Orators said Mother they the said Confederates doe further pretend
that the said Mr. Gorges dyed first & that the said Mr Rogers was the survivor of them and that they the said Confederates have revailed with the heire of the said Mr Rogers so as that such heire hath Conveyed the said premisses to the said Sir Henry Goodrick his heires & assignes & they the said Confederates
doe pretend that by such meanes as aforesaid the said Thomas Merricke is Intitled & hath Entred on the said premisses for the residue to come of the said terme of One thousand yeares Subject to redemption on payment of the said Summe of Three thousand pounds or Some Such Summe with Interest therefore
and that the said Sir Henry Goodricke is intitled to the [R]evercion Inheritance & Equity of redempcion of the said whole premisses And that your Orator hath no right or title thereof or to any part thereof either in Law or Equity whereas the [truth] is as the said Confederates well know that your Orators said Father &
Mother at the time of their pretended mortgaging of the said premisses to the said Sir Thomas Higgins had no reall Occacion to borrow Any such summe of money nor did they borrow the same of or make such mortgages or security to the said Sir Thomas Higgons or if they
did the same was [d]uly in Colour to protect their Estate from the Violence of such [tim]es as they feared was coming on those of their Religion they being professed papists or if the said money was really lent & the said Security really given therefore the same was taken
up to provide for themselves against such times or for some other Ends unknowne to your Orator And the same money was again repaid to the said Sir Thomas Higgons or his Assignes or at least the Same was paid & satisfyed by your Orators said Father & mother or one of
them by and out of the money ariseing by the sale of certain lands of your Orators said Ancestors at Lockston aforesaid in the said County of Somersett included in the said mortgage or Security & the same mortgages ought not to have been assigned & kept on foot as the Same is
pretended to have been as aforesaid Much less ought the said premisses to have been charged with any further Summes as is pretended the same have been as aforesaid nor had Your Orators said Mother at the times of the pretended so charging of the said premisses power so to doe to that the same mortgages & Securityes
ought to be avoided & Set aside as against Your Orator & the Same doe not comprehend all the said premisses But Your Orator in honour to his Mother & Family & to obtain a full discovery of the said Settlements assurances & writings is ready & willing to pay the said Thomas Merrick what is Justly due
to him on the account aforesaid upon his assigning of all his Estate & Interest in the said premisses to your Orator or whom he shall appoint & in the meantime to con[firace] the said mortgaged premisses to him Subject to redempcion by Your Orator on payment of what shall appeare to be really
and [timely] due to him on the Same provided he the said Mr Merrick & his Agent the said Mr Edwards doe make full discovery to Your Orator [of all] the said deeds Settlements assureances & writings as are or have beene in their or either of their Custody or power And the said Second Fine so levyed by Your
Orators said Father & Mother as aforesaid if any such was so levyed for none other End but to confirme the said Security to the said Sir Thomas Higgons & ought not to be Carryed to any further purpose especially against Your Orator & of your Orators said Mother did make any such Conveyance to the said
Mr Gorges & Mr Rogers as aforesaid Yet She had not Sufficent power so to doe or if she had Yet the Same was intended cheifely to preserve the [Saconib] of the said Estate during the Coverture between her & the said Mr Glanvile to her own Seperate use to the [End] the [m]ight be enabled the better to provide for Support
maintain & educate Your Orator & his Said Sister & principally to preserve the Inheritance of the said Estate for Your Orator & for his benefitt from & against the power & attempts of her said husband & ought to be carryed no further muchlesse to the utter disinherit[on] of your Orator & ruined of him & all the rest of
his said Mothers Children as the same is attempted by the said Confederates to be Your Orator [or] any of the said other Children having never been extravagent or disobedient or undutifull to their said Mother And if your Orator has ever owned himselfe guilty of any such thing by letter or otherwise
It was so written & done only to please her and if your Orators said Mother did make any such Will or deed of appointment to or in favour of the said Sir Henry Goodrick as aforesaid Yet the Same was not pursuant to her power or not duely executed or attested Nor had she any the least [Colone]
of authority to make an Executor But perticularly (tho with great Reluctancy) Your Orator doth charge as the [hirth] is that his said Mother was not a woman of a Sound Sedate & disposing mind memory or understanding of of a due Sanity of mind & Capacity of understanding to make a will or
dispose of her Estate for that after the said Seperacion of her & her husband & She not being able to hear any thing of him not Soe much as whether he went or what became of him nor whether he was dead or living She became very Melancholy occasioned sometime by her reflecting on her Conduct
towards him & at other times by her dread of his returne & avenging himselfe on her as the pretended he threatned at his departure She became Lunatick & not capable of managing her Estate much lesse of the disposing of the Inheritance of it Insomuch that she did not make cleere Fifty
pounds per annum of her whole Estate as she upon Occacion deposed & She lived under the rate of Fifty pounds a yeare to all appearances & Yet [fit be tine] as the Confederates pretend She hath so extravagantly run out of & charged her Estate as aforesaid & in respect of her Family she was often
without any Cause in [clead] sometimes of her Tennants Sometimes of her Servants Sometimes of her Children & at other times of all of them that they would kill her or at least betray & deliver her up to her husband who as she pretended intended to carry her into a forreigne Country where none of her friends
should ever see or hear of her & Chain her to a post & feed her only with bread & water [Allas] her said husband never attempted to come near her nor so much as troubled himselfe about her nor did he ever send to or any ways correspond with them or any of them nor had She the least ground for any Such
[thrends] or Fear But Yet she would hide herselfe & Sometimes lock herselfe upp from them & at other times goe they knew not where & Sometimes beyond the [Seas] & She was so farr distracted in her mind that She proposed to have her Bull paced to make a pad of him & have her houses thatched with
pebles or round stones to have Man cutt down a tree of severall Tons & carry it on his Back to make a Ladder & use without her necessary Cloaths to goe out at break of day on the Do[wnes] amongst the Fa[rze] & gather Butterflyes worms & other Insects in order as she would Say to Send them
to London to have their pictures drawne & as may be instanced in many other things & Soe unaccountably She behaved herselfe towards her Children that when Your Orator came of age of One & twenty Yeares She sent him to the West Indies with only twenty pounds Stock to make a Merchant of him as She
pretended & he having the misfortune to be taken by French privateer and being afterwards taken by an Englishman of [hiarr] & brought home She forbad her Servants & Tennants to receive or entertain him or so much as to allow him a Bed & would have had him hanged as a pyrate And afterwards
she did assigne him a Farme of thirty pounds per annum for three yeares to live on & Set him up a Farmer on it & gave him Some [Sheepe] & Cattle manage it with a [xxxx] Your Orator did with great diligence & Industry for about Six weekes when She took occasion to send Your Orator from home in an Errand for her &
on the morrow before Your Orator could possibly returne she took away all his stock again giving out that the Farmer meaning Your Orator was broke & [runn] away & on that occasion at his returne obliging him under Colour of [re]signing up the said Farm to her & without any well Consideration to
release or assigne to her all his Interest in the whole Estate of his Ancestors & [farme] the [r]ented [estate] now [unjustly] make use against Your Orator & She Sent Your Orator to board at a papists house in Cheshire whether at her Comand he went with only one Guinea in his pocket & being come thither the house appeared to be
full before & Your Orator was refused recepcion to that he was forced to begg his way home & afterwards she perswaded your Orator to goe to a Monastary in Flanders & become a Monk altho She had not given him Educacion or opportunity of learning exceeding the quality of a parish clerke And Your Orator
humbly shewed his dislike of such an undertaking but in obedience to her Submitted to her pleasure & accordingly went to [xxxxxx] in Flanders to a Monastary there to [which] he was directed & there continued about nine Months when he found that instead of a Monk he was to be but a Monks Servant [which]
as he conceived he had no reason to Submitt to but refused so to be & returned home begging his way having had of his said Mother but Five pounds to support him in the nine months expedicion And afterwards she would have him goe to France to be as she said bredd a Gentleman & accordingly at her Comand he went to a
Gentleman She directed there where Your Orator continued about two yeares & in all that time had but half a Guinea of her of her so that for want he was for want he was forced to returne home & in Your Orators absence it being reported that he was dead Your Orators said mother said she [would] give Five pounds for the Certainty thereof for that then She said She could Sell
